Lagrange's Remainder Formula states that:

\begin{align*}
R_n(x) &=f(x)-T_n(x) \\
&= \frac{f^{(n+1)}(c)}{(n+1)!}(x-a)^{(n+1)}
\end{align*} Where $c$ is a number in $[x, a].$

When $R_n(x)$ is positive, then $T_n(x)$ is an underestimate; if it is
negative, then $T_n(x)$ is an overestimate. For this problem,

\begin{align*}
f(x) &=\sqrt[3]{x} = x^{1/3} \\
f'(x) &=\frac{1}{3x^{2/3}}\\
f''(x) &= -\frac{2}{9x^{5/3}}\\
f'''(x) &= \frac{10}{(27 x^{8/3})} \\
(x-a)^{(n+1)} &= (8.1-8)^3 = 0.001
\end{align*}

Since $f(8.1)$ and $(x-a)^{n+1}$ are both positive, we can conclude that
$R_n(8.1)$ is also positive since the factorial is positive as well.
This means that:

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle
T_2(8.1)<\sqrt[3]{8.1}
\end{align*}

